# Todo App — Full Stack Deployment on GCP with CI/CD

A full stack Todo application deployed across two separate GCP virtual machines, with automated CI/CD pipelines that push changes to production on every commit. This project demonstrates a real-world DevOps workflow: infrastructure provisioning, reverse proxy configuration, process management, and end-to-end automation using GitHub Actions.

---

## The Application

A simple Todo app where users can create, complete, and delete tasks. Nothing fancy on the surface — but the infrastructure behind it reflects patterns used in real production deployments: separate servers for frontend and backend, traffic routed through a reverse proxy, and zero manual steps needed to ship a code change.

**Frontend:** Create React App (React 18), communicates with the backend via REST API calls using `axios`.

**Backend:** Node.js + Express, exposes a REST API at `/api/todos` with full CRUD support (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE).

---

## Architecture

```
Developer
    │
    │  git push
    ▼
GitHub ──── triggers ────▶ GitHub Actions
                                │
                    ┌───────────┴───────────┐
                    │ SSH deploy            │ SSH deploy
                    ▼                       ▼
           ┌─────────────────┐    ┌──────────────────┐
           │   Backend VM    │    │   Frontend VM    │
           │  34.35.151.43   │    │  34.35.16.106    │
           │                 │    │                  │
           │  Nginx :80      │    │  Nginx :80       │
           │     ↓           │    │     ↓            │
           │  PM2            │    │  PM2 + serve     │
           │     ↓           │    │     ↓            │
           │  Express :3000  │    │  CRA build/      │
           └─────────────────┘    └──────────────────┘
                    ▲                       │
                    │   HTTP /api/todos     │
                    └───────────────────────┘
                            Browser
```

The frontend and backend live on completely separate VMs. The browser loads the React app from the frontend VM, then makes direct API calls to the backend VM using an environment variable (`REACT_APP_API_URL`) baked into the build at deploy time.

---

## DevOps Stack

| Tool | Role |
|---|---|
| **GCP Compute Engine** | Cloud VMs hosting the backend and frontend |
| **Ubuntu 22.04** | OS on both VMs |
| **Nginx** | Reverse proxy — routes public port 80 traffic to the internal app port |
| **PM2** | Process manager — keeps apps running, auto-restarts on crash, survives VM reboots |
| **`serve`** | Lightweight static file server for the CRA production build |
| **GitHub Actions** | CI/CD — runs on every push to `master`, builds and deploys to both VMs over SSH |
| **ufw** | OS-level firewall — opens ports 22 (SSH) and 80 (HTTP) |
| **Bash** | Provisioning scripts that set up each VM from scratch |
| **npm / npm ci** | Dependency management — `npm ci` used in all automated contexts for reproducible installs |

